  "prompt": "What is the difference between adding and committing in Git?",
  "response": "In Git, the concepts of \"adding\" and \"committing\" are two distinct steps in the workflow of tracking changes in a project. Here's an overview of the differences between the two:\n\n### Adding (git add)\n\n1. **Staging Changes**: The `git add` command is used to add changes to the staging area (also known as the index). When you use `git add`, you are marking changes in your working directory that you want to include in the next commit.\n\n2. **Selective Changes**: You can choose specific files or parts of files to stage. For example, you can add a single file with `git add <filename>` or multiple files with `git add .` or `git add *.txt` to add all text files.\n\n3. **Temporary State**: The staging area is a temporary holding area, allowing you to prepare your changes for the next commit, giving you control over what gets included in the commit.\n\n### Committing (git commit)\n\n1. **Creating a Snapshot**: The `git commit` command takes the changes that have been added to the staging area and creates a new commit in the repository's history. This commit serves as a snapshot of your project's state at that point in time.\n\n2. **Message and Metadata**: When you commit, you provide a commit message that describes what changes you made. This message is essential for understanding the history of the project. Each commit also includes metadata, such as the author, timestamp, and unique commit hash.\n\n3. **Permanent Record**: Once a commit is made, it becomes a permanent part of the Git history. You can refer to it, revert to it, or view it later.\n\n### Summary\n\n- **`git add`**: Stages changes, marking them for inclusion in the next commit.\n- **`git commit`**: Takes staged changes and creates a new entry in the version history, recording the state of the repository along with a message and other metadata.\n\nIn general, you first use `git add` to prepare your changes and then use `git commit` to save those changes permanently to the repository.",
